184
00:07:50,874 --> 00:07:52,907
by reducing the temperature to 30 degrees celsius.

185
00:07:52,974 --> 00:07:54,940
You can choose to make adjustments on

186
00:07:54,974 --> 00:07:58,740
the type of mold, the water portion and the storage place after molding.

187
00:07:59,487 --> 00:08:01,553
But imagine it's winter now,

188
00:08:01,553 --> 00:08:04,607
and the only mold you have is thin-walled mold,

189
00:08:04,738 --> 00:08:05,887
what should you do then?

190
00:08:06,143 --> 00:08:09,471
You can keep the temperature of soap mixture higher in the beginning of soapmaking process

191
00:08:09,983 --> 00:08:11,775
or add some milk to help raise the temperature

192
00:08:12,031 --> 00:08:14,591
and put the mold into cooler box to keep it warm.

193
00:08:15,103 --> 00:08:18,431
However, if you use this type of mold with thicker walls

194
00:08:18,943 --> 00:08:20,223
and with wonden box and lid

195
00:08:20,479 --> 00:08:22,783
then you can choose not to insulate the soap.

196
00:08:24,575 --> 00:08:26,367
I will give one more example of household soap

197
00:08:26,623 --> 00:08:28,695
because household soap really cracks easily

198
00:08:28,695 --> 00:08:32,511
which is especially challenging for newbies.

199
00:08:32,767 --> 00:08:34,832
If the mold you use for making household soap

200
00:08:34,866 --> 00:08:36,699
is a thin-walled mold like this

201
00:08:36,732 --> 00:08:39,679
or a PP5 plastic container like this

202
00:08:40,191 --> 00:08:41,983
they have very good heat dissipating properties,

203
00:08:42,239 --> 00:08:44,287
so the soap will not crack easily under such conditions

204
00:08:44,543 --> 00:08:46,847
and there is no need to put the soap into fridge for cooling.

205
00:08:47,359 --> 00:08:51,199
But if you use mold with good insulating properties like this,

206
00:08:51,455 --> 00:08:53,503
